USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the smartest man's reputation, as a diligent student repeats on the Afghan issue the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself took for the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his Afghan approach, eagerly awaited, it was proved to be a copy of the script used for Iraq by Bush, created three years ago.
Not only is the speech "just like in Iraq" used in the same text several times, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A new way forward."
It was he himself who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, the country he is suffering from civil war. And that he criticized it as "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences."
The following months, however, showed that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful, so that nothing is spoken of in Iraq today in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, yet objectively left his successor a much more favorable initial situation than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will be repeated.
The camp captains again asked for the increase in the military contingent, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal. He, even despite traditional subordinate relations, subjected undecided riflemen in the White House to harsh criticism.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't think of anything better, so he at least tricked the general over 10,000 military personnel.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself previously had at least 10,000.
The most problematic of Obama's entire strategy seems his goal, to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and finish this procedure in three years. Obama's entire doctrine generated more questions from the answers he offered.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars in recent years, Iraq's society is relatively well organized, its leaders respect the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: it is not possible to trust anyone and no agreement is reached.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare the Afghan security forces, if they are accustomed to changing the chief every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, although formally established, will remain only a people of Potemkin. After him, patriarchal tribal relations will remain.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated because of confusing relations, even more complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even establishing a state that is "able of action," a minimum target of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is bucked by his voluntarism.
For the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to worsen and is now about to erupt.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing about reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "go home soon" will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting the date of the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will consider it an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents what the security of Germany or Italy has with the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, capable of radically affecting the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: to try to solve the problem with military force or not.
It will be necessary to look for answers precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, each solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive point for Barack Obama is the fact that three years to go before the presidential elections and that is why there is still plenty of time to find another strategy, if this proves a total failure.
