A Czech discovery: an effective substance even in the 'encalled' HIV virus
Team of Czech and German scientists tests new compounds capable of moderating the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective in a common variant of the virus, as some already accessible medicines.
AIDS disease cannot be cured until now.
However, patients' lives can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of drugs that prevent the replication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, the drugs no longer work.
The work of the experts from three Institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VoCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg demonstrates the possibility of mastering the resistance of the virus.
They found that substances called metalcarbors have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbers are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently from all the drugs used today, and that's why they can solve the resistance problem.
In their work, scientists find new, improved - compounds, prepared knowing the molecular mechanism of their link to the albumin of the virus.
Metalocarbons have a single three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A traitor and resistant virus
HIV proteasis is an albumin of the HIV virus, and is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV proteasis, HIV virus fractionation does not occur and mature and virus corpuscles would not be created.
