Management revolution or end of business intelligence?
If nothing changes in the management of the big French companies, our struggle for the development of business intelligence will have been in vain...
More than ten years ago, the attitude of the management of large companies towards their employees recalls the position of companies towards consumers before the marketing revolution: it is that the collaborators adhere to "values" determined from above as before it was about imposing products thought by factory technicians on consumers.
By putting the customer at the center of the company, the marketing revolution gave its place to the strategies of conquering the markets... although the authoritarian temptation to impose products that are not related to the factors of preference of the customers is repeated regularly.
An employee demobilization may end in a deadly demoralization.
Suicides at France Telecom, PSA or Renault are just the tip of the iceberg of a much more general phenomenon that particularly affects executives.
This demobilization seriously compromises the development of all the intellectual functions of the company, especially R &amp; D and, even more, of business intelligence.
Indeed, the BI (Business Intelligence) "requires that all parties involved (...) have proactive conduct and a prospective vision"; it needs a commitment on the part of employees that is completely opposed to the recommendations of an authoritarian management.
For this reason, we are calling for a managerial revolution, which would consist of putting the collaborators at the centre of the company's concerns as well as the customer.
Internal opinion polls have relative utility
Will internal opinion polls, such as the questionnaire conducted by Orange among its employees, incite the managerial revolution in practice?
Unfortunately, I'm afraid not.
-In principle, because I was able to verify that, in the face of a new situation, and after many laps, all companies end up doing essentially... what they always did. B989
- Secondly, because authoritarianism, one of the pathologies of power, grows proportionally to the importance of its own failures.
- Finally, because most managers have a simplistic view of human behavior.
As they come from the great engineering schools, they interpret psychology in a mechanistic way.
They adopt, by intellectual comfort, the ancient behavioral theory that American "neurosciences" recently revived, and that the Institutes of Studies and the media spread widely behind their backs.
In this way, by suggesting that it is possible to manage the "commands" (sic) of the executives' commitment, a recent Ipsos investigation published on Le Figaro.fr reaffirms managers in a mechanistic management position, unfit to the world today.
Identifying and measuring mobilization factors
On the contrary, the managerial revolution necessary for the proper functioning of modern enterprises implies adopting a finalist vision of human behavior.
It consists of integrating into every reasoning or practice of business management, a fundamental fact: for employees, commitment to the company is only possible if it appears clearly as a means to realize part of its dreams, ambitions and projects.
Today, only studies from the Motifunctional Analysis adopt this conception of employees' motivations.
Studies showed that they judge their company based on a default doxa that allows them, through the image they have of the company, to evaluate what it offers them to achieve their own life projects.
Thanks to the identification and measurement of mobilization factors, company managers can control, foresee and anticipate their "social performance" and relocate human resources management "in the place."
In this way, they create a favorable terrain for the organized development of strong and effective business intelligence.
