The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa found looked the same as many other carnivorous dinosaurs: an animal two meters long and 1.50 meters high that ran on the two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp and curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of years later, this wouldn't have been something special.
But the Tawa found was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues in Thursday's journal Science.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which at the time was in a dry area of the supercontinent Pangea on the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, Nesbitt says.
It shows us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the propagation and characteristics of the early dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began an excavation in 2006 at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
"Sometimes, we've found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, this is unprecedented for Triassic sediments," says Randall Irmis, a team member of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they collected the remains of five specimens.
A finding confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, it's an exceptional finding: "The dinosaur fossils of the Triassic are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments are found."
Other dinosaur experts do not fully share such enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, Martin Sander of the University of Bonn says for example.
According to the current current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the older fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts discuss, for example, when saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: carnivorous theropods among those of Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also birds, quadruped sauropods known as "long neck" and their relatives, and the Ornithischia herbivores (sail with bird pelvis), to which, for example, the species Triceratops and Ste- Igosaurus.
According to analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa finds is a primitive theropod.
This one shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, Nesbitt says.
For example, in Tawa's skull, researchers found signs of air bags, such as those also possessed by the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to the air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa's case, the bones of the spine were evidently filled with air in part.
Tawa is the theropod with older, primitive air bags, Randall Irmis says.
Because the related line of the subsequent giant sauropods also had air bags and light bones, it was likely that the common predecessors of both groups would already produce this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs so far known lived in South America, the researchers deduce that the saurians first emerged there.
Therefore, the three genealogical lineages were initially separated and spread from South America to every corner of the Earth, which at the time still formed a unique Earth mass, the Pangea supercontinent.
However, the facts say the team found along with Tawa to find the remains of two other not closely-minded theropods.
All three cannot descend from a uniquely related predecessor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are opponents, too.
An even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to a sister group of the dinosaurs, lived in present-day Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His opinion could give a distorted image, because simply in South America many dinosaur fossils continue to be preserved, while on other continents there is hardly anything to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral line from reptiles to the dominant terrestrial vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains an enigma.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs and many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic the dinosaurs spread all over the world and many new species developed, while kinship became extinct at the Triassic boundary to the Jurassic.
Successful stories weren't eternal
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
It may have been given a massive extinction that dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs were better adapted, so they were able to beat the opponents in the area.
Successful stories are not always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact is the boom of a group of species, which had also evolved in the Triassic and since then carried a miserable existence: mammals.
