Psychosis is a hard and painful disease but it also involves something positive and creative - madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has researched so-called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as a dream.
Thirheal hallucinations are almost very complex and detailed dreams that the person who experiences them considers real and that can no longer differentiate from being awake.
Thirhement conscious states arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or disease, such as in patients with polyradiaculopathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious. die bei vollem Bewusstsein eine motorische L.hmung erleben.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of oneself or the world due to a total and permanent motor incapacity, it replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of its own and imaginary that is decoupled from reality.
A form of borderline situation between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, there is a change of world, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an unbearable situation itself that our own capacity for creation allows us not to sink into the nowhere to loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen, of Zurich, also describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as a soul-rescuing action.
He was 49 when his conscience embarked on several-day trips after a heart transplant operation with a heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility at the intensive care station.
Claussen immersed himself in a world created by it and visited strange places of other times: he was lying in bed, an older man aboard a sanatorium on a train, a robot watched for his health.
