Seventy-five per cent of working mothers have had problems with their motherhood
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of younger generations who want to be mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fashion and career of women in Spain', prepared by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers have been limited in opportunities in the workplace due to maternity.
The study points out that there are many differences in the beginning of cohabitation as a couple and the number of children, depending on whether or not they work and the type of work they carry out.
Those who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time, or have an unstable job, start cohabitation as a couple before, advance the first maternity, and have more children.
On the contrary, women in stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay coexistence and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years of age with fixed work have the first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting cohabitation, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time than their life trajectory to achieve them, which has led them to postpone the union and arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed exerts a lot of influence on motherhood although less on the schedule of pairing," explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of study is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they marry and having the first offspring.
According to the survey, the higher the educational level, the higher the age at which they marry and the first child.
The difference is also maintained between women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with elementary and higher education have been mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 on average respectively.
"Another division is also established between women according to their level of education.
While those who have elementary education marry and have their first child before getting a stable job, those with middle or higher levels invest this sequence and give priority to obtaining stable work as a precondition for marriage and the arrival of a child," Delgado details.
