Emergency braking aid is already mandatory
As with the ABS brake-blocking and will go through the ESP stability control, emergency braking support systems will have to be a mandatory element in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all cars and light commercial vehicles of new registration, while for the rest a period of deficiency is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase the protection of pedestrians, although, because of their way of working, it can also help to avoid many collisions by range.
The emergency brake assistant what it does is increase the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects through the tram of the driver.
But this one doesn't always keep that pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by car component manufacturer Bosch, a third of drivers involved in an accident had not stepped on the brake before the collision and half of them did not take full advantage of the force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum to the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to an EU study itself, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be avoided each year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four casualties with damage to people would be avoided - when so-called intelligent emergency braking systems are popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (through a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps him by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device exerts maximum effort on the brakes to minimize damage.
